Using Regex and pattern matching. The tweets are cleaned and text corpus is created.

#____________________________________________#Cleaning tweets______________________________________
clean_text = function(tweet) {
tweet <-tolower(tweet$text)
tweet = stringr::str_replace_all(tweet, "[^a-zA-Z#@0-9\\s]", "") #remove unwanted word
tweet = stringr::str_replace_all(tweet, "http.*", "") #remove httpslink
tweet = stringr::str_replace_all(tweet, "brt ", "") # remove retweets
tweet = stringr::str_replace_all(tweet, "^[b]", "") # 
tweet = stringr::str_replace_all(tweet, "amp", "") # 
tweet = gsub("^ ", "", tweet)  # remove blank spaces at the beginning
tweet = gsub(" $", "", tweet) # remove blank spaces at the end
tweet = gsub("\\\\x.*? |\\\\x.*?\'$|\\\\x.*?\"$","", tweet) #  some peculiar pattern
return (tweet)
} # Clean text function ends
text_corpus = clean_text(tweet1)

Extracting Various details from the clean corpus created above and the same is converted into a data frame with folloiwng three columns

  1. Text message
  2. Twitter Handler (use detail)
  3. Hashtag
#______________________________#Extracting and Savings hashtag and user details in a dataframe____
detail = function(corpus) {
df <- NULL
df$user_detail= stringr::str_extract_all(corpus,"@\\w+") # extracting user detail
df$hashtag = stringr::str_extract_all(corpus,"#\\w+") #Extracting hashtag
df$text= stringr::str_replace_all(corpus,"#\\w+", "") #removing hashtag
df$text = stringr::str_replace_all(df$text,"@\\w+", "") # removing user detail
df$text = gsub("[[:punct:]]","",df$text) #remove any unwanted punctuation from the text
df$text= gsub("^ ", "", df$text)  # remove blank spaces at the beginning
df$text= gsub("\\s+$", "", df$text) # remove blank spaces at the end
clean_tweet <-as.data.frame(do.call("cbind", df))
return (clean_tweet)
} # Extracting various detail from text
clean_df = detail(text_corpus)

Created a word analyzer function which takes input clean text corpus and analyze them based on either monogram or bigram and tokenize it. The fnction returns return a list of

  1. Dtm
  2. Dataframe,
  3. Top words,
  4. Wordcloud
word_analyzer = function(txt,ngrams){
  text_df <- data_frame(line = 1:length(txt), text2 = unlist(txt))
  #__________________________________#Analyzing text using tidytext format (uni-bi-grams)___________________
  word_token_grams = text_df %>% unnest_tokens(word,text2,token = "ngrams", n = ngrams) %>% anti_join(stop_words) %>% 
    count(word, sort = TRUE) %>% mutate(id = 1)
  if (ngrams == 1) 
  { 
    word_grams <- cast_dtm(word_token_grams,document = id,term = word,value = n)
    data_gram <- data.frame(word_token_grams)
    top_words <- word_token_grams %>% filter(n > 50) %>% mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>% ggplot(aes(word, n)) +geom_col() +
      xlab(NULL) +coord_flip()
    set.seed(1234)
    wc<- wordcloud(words = data_gram$word, freq = data_gram$n, min.freq = 1,
              max.words=200, random.order=FALSE, rot.per=0.35, 
              colors=brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"))
    mylist <- list("dtm" = word_grams, "df" = data_gram, "top_words" = top_words, "wordcloud" = wc)
  }
  
  else {
    #____________________________# separate bigrams
    bigrams_separated <- word_token_grams %>%
      separate(word, c("word1", "word2"), sep = " ") 
    #____________________________# filtered bigrams
    bigrams_filtered <- bigrams_separated %>%
      filter(!word1 %in% stop_words$word) %>%
      filter(!word2 %in% stop_words$word)
    #____________________________# bigrams united
    bigrams_united <- bigrams_filtered %>%
      unite(word, word1, word2, sep = " ")
    #____________________________#Create DTM of Bigrams
    word_grams <- cast_dtm(bigrams_united,document = id,term = word,value = n) 
    #________________________________#Creating plot for most occuring word for bigrams
    data_gram <- data.frame(bigrams_united)
    top_words <- bigrams_united %>% filter(n > 20) %>% mutate(word = reorder(word, n)) %>% ggplot(aes(word, n)) +geom_col() +
      xlab(NULL) +coord_flip()
    set.seed(1234)
    wc<- wordcloud(words = data_gram$word, freq = data_gram$n, min.freq = 1,
                   max.words=200, random.order=FALSE, rot.per=0.35, 
                   colors=brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"))
    mylist <- list("dtm" = word_grams, "df" = data_gram, "top_words" = top_words, "wordcloud" = wc)
  }
  return(mylist)
}

#_________________________________#Top 5 unigrams, hashtag and user profile______________________________
top_profile <- function(cleantext) {
text_df <- data_frame(text2 = unlist(cleantext$text))
top_5_words = text_df %>% unnest_tokens(word, text2) %>% anti_join(stop_words) %>% count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%   
 rename(count = n) %>% head(5L)


text_user <- data_frame(user = unlist(cleantext$user_detail))
top_5_user = text_user %>% unnest_tokens(word, user) %>% anti_join(stop_words) %>% count(word, sort = TRUE) %>% 
  rename(count = n) %>% head(5L)
  
text_hashtag <- data_frame(hashtag = unlist(cleantext$hashtag))
top_5_hashtag = text_hashtag %>% unnest_tokens(word, hashtag) %>% anti_join(stop_words) %>% count(word, sort = TRUE) %>%   
  rename(count = n)  %>% head(n=5L)

top_dataframe <- data.frame(top_5_words,top_5_hashtag,top_5_user)
colnames(top_dataframe) <- c("Top Words", "Count of  top words", "Top Hashtag", "Count of Hashtag", "Top handler","Count of handler")
return(top_dataframe)
}
top_df = top_profile(clean_df)

#__________________________________________#Creating DTM and TFIDF using text2vec__________________
t <- as.character(clean_df$text)
stop = as.character(stop_words$word)
it = itoken(t, progressbar = FALSE)
v = create_vocabulary(it,stopwords= stop) %>% prune_vocabulary(doc_proportion_max = 0.2, term_count_min = 5)    # can change this parm for overly large corpora
vectorizer = vocab_vectorizer(v)
dtm = create_dtm(it, vectorizer)

Performing Latent semantic analysis of the created DTM.

I tried to create clustering in the IBM Research tweets data. In order to find the optimal number of clusters, i have employed elbow curve to find optimal number of clusters..

Bylooking at the elbow curve, we can say that optimal number of clusters seems around 10, but error is very high of about (~212)

By looking at within sum of squares(WSS) error, i have assumed cluster to be at 51 though cluster 60 has minimum WSS error but the error is increasing beyond 51.

The result looks interesting.
